    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm a bit stuck on a syntax tree for a sentence in my intro class. If I have the sentence \"The student saw the professor with the telescope,\" I'm seeing two different ways to parse the PP \"with the telescope.\" One version attaches it to the NP \"the professor,\" but my textbook shows it attaching to the VP \"saw.\" Can you explain the structural difference in how those branches are drawn and why the VP attachment is a valid reading?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The structural difference is where the prepositional phrase (PP) attaches in the tree diagram. When attached to \"the professor\" (the NP), the PP modifies the noun, telling us *which* professor. When attached to \"saw\" (the VP), the PP is an adverbial modifier, telling us *how* the seeing occurred. The VP attachment is valid because you can interpret the sentence as meaning the student used the telescope to see the professor.",
      "source": "target",
